++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++insertAdjacentHTML()
insertAdjacentHTML() is a JavaScript method that allows you to insert HTML code into a specific position relative to an element in the DOM (Document Object Model). It can be used to add new content to a web page without overwriting the existing content.

The method takes two arguments:

1) A string that specifies the position where you want to insert the HTML code. The possible values are:
'beforebegin': inserts the HTML code before the element itself.
'afterbegin': inserts the HTML code as the first child of the element.
'beforeend': inserts the HTML code as the last child of the element.
'afterend': inserts the HTML code after the element itself.
2) A string that contains the HTML code you want to insert.
Here is an example of how to use insertAdjacentHTML() to insert a new paragraph after an existing one:

const existingParagraph = document.querySelector('p');
existingParagraph.insertAdjacentHTML('afterend', '<p>This is a new paragraph</p>');//ç¬¬äºŒä¸ªå‚æ•°å¯ä»¥å†™ä¸€ä¸ªå˜é‡ï¼Œå˜é‡é‡Œå¯ä»¥ç”¨``å†™ä»»ä½•html

This code will add a new paragraph after the existing one.


